      "outline_claim": "An exponential envelope dominates any finite-order score growth, so the weighted negative gradient vanishes in the far field.",
      "paragraph_claim": "Under the registered finite-order score-growth assumption, the exponential remoteness envelope drives the weighted far-field contribution to zero without asserting that sample utility itself decays exponentially.",
      "reader_question": "Why use the exponential form rather than an arbitrary taper?",
      "reviewer_objection": "The exponential form may be an arbitrary utility-decay assumption.",
      "role": "Provide the method-level tail guarantee without inventing a utility-decay law.",
      "section": "Distributionally Robust Policy Optimization",
      "sentence_plan": [
        {
          "instruction": "State that the exponential form is chosen for a tail-control property, not a utility model.",
          "role": "motivation"
        },
        {
          "instruction": "Introduce the finite-order bound C(1+r)^k on the unweighted score-times-advantage norm.",
          "role": "assumption"
        },
        {
          "instruction": "State that exp(-lambda r) dominates every finite polynomial order and makes the weighted term vanish.",
          "role": "analytic_result"
        },
        {
          "instruction": "Exclude universal taper rankings and exponential utility-decay interpretations.",
          "role": "claim_boundary"
        }
      ],
